{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is module handoff: file discovery + filename parsing/sorting + migration execution order. A pure Unit test of sort logic can miss wiring bugs where discovered files are not the same list that gets executed. Rejected higher level: behavior text does not require real subprocess/OS/network effects beyond local module wiring, and has no AI dependency.","test_description":"Run the real runner against a temp `migrations/` directory containing out-of-order files (e.g., `001_...sql`, `010_...sql`, `002_...sql`) and a test DB. Assert side effects show execution order `001 -> 002 -> 010` (for example via inserted audit rows or ordered metadata timestamps).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is persisted state handoff across runs (`_migrations` metadata + executor). Unit tests for a single skip function are insufficient to catch real rerun regressions across runner/database modules. Rejected higher level: behavior text does not require real OS/subprocess conditions; no model output dependency.","test_description":"Execute runner twice against the same test DB and same migration files where a migration has observable side effects if rerun. Assert first run applies it once and second run performs no second side effect while metadata remains single-entry per migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real DB transaction behavior under failure plus runner control flow. Mocked repositories/fake DBs commonly hide rollback semantics and statement-level failure behavior, so MOCK-HIDE applies. Rejected lower levels: failure mode is tied to real database execution semantics, not just in-process wiring.","test_description":"Against a real PostgreSQL instance, provide migrations where one file performs a write then fails, followed by another migration file. Run runner and assert: (1) writes from failing migration are absent (rolled back), (2) later migration was not attempted, (3) failed migration is not marked applied.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires concurrent separate processes and shared database contention. This crosses process/OS scheduling boundaries and real DB locking/constraint behavior; in-process mocks cannot reproduce the race reliably. Rejected lower levels: Integration cannot validate true multi-process concurrency failure modes.","test_description":"Start two runner processes simultaneously against the same real PostgreSQL DB and identical migration set. Assert each migration’s side effects and `_migrations` records appear exactly once total, with no duplicates and no missed migrations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.93,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is ordering/wiring between bootstrap logic and migration apply loop. This is a local module interaction and can be caught by running the real runner against a fresh DB state and verifying observed order. Rejected higher level: behavior text does not require subprocess-specific behavior beyond normal runner execution, and has no AI dependency.","test_description":"Run runner once on a fresh test DB with at least one migration. Assert `_migrations` exists before first migration bookkeeping occurs (e.g., first migration succeeds without missing-table errors and metadata insert succeeds in same run), and resulting metadata reflects correct first-run bootstrap.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
